\begin_layout Subsection
Target object
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The object observed was the spiral galaxy NGC 7331, located at a distance
 of 12.2 ± 1.0 Mpc from Earth.
 It is located in the constellation Pegasus, and its equatorial coordinates
 are 22h 37m 04.1s RA and +34° 24' 56'' Dec.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bias and flat noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before observations began, 5 images with exposure time of 0.00001 seconds
 were taken in order to obtain data that was later used to compensate for
 bias.
 No photons were allowed to enter the CCD while these images were taken.
 In addition to this, 5 images of exposure time of 2 seconds under a flat
 bright light field were performed in order to properly compensate for imperfect
ions in the subsequent image acquisition.
\end_layout

